If you're feeling stuck, or inspiration just isn't striking, try taking the focus off forcing creativity. INSTEAD, try getting really curious & ask a lot of different questions.
.
I wonder what I would do in this situation?
I wonder how the character might feel if they lived in California instead of New York?
What if the characters were reversed?
What would a picture look like from this angle instead of that?
How would I feel if my child went to school but didn't come home?
What questions would you have if a woman showed up claiming her child belonged to your spouse?
What might have happened if you went to sleep one night & woke up in an operating table?
What are some occasions where a person commits a horrible crime but you'd give them a pass?
What kinds of things might you enjoy if your favorite color was sea foam green?
.
Get the idea? But asking a lot of questions, often something will shake loose. Maybe a plot point changes in a way that makes more sense or believability. Maybe a spark of something you can use in your current project strikes because you've stopped trying to force it to the surface.
.
Regardless, if you focus more on asking questions rather than waiting for creativity to return, you can keep pressing forward, which in turn tends to renew your inspiration.
.

A HOLIDAY REMINDER: Your only responsibilities this season (and all seasons) are to ☝🏼 communicate your needs effectively and ✌🏼 protect your space & take care of you.
.
I had a really great chat with my therapist yesterday and while we continue to unpack unresolved childhood trauma, she so rightly pointed out that when I say ABC makes me wonder if I SHOULD be more like XYZ... that SHOULD'ING stems from feeling of shame or guilt at expectations wrongly placed on you by yourself or someone else that cause feelings of failure, brokenness, or inadequacy.
.
And I feel like this is a great reminder for the holidays, when we watch other moms doing all the things that maybe we even wish we were doing, but also for ALL THE TIME.
.
There is no such thing as what you SHOULD be doing in order to be a great parent, or give your kids a joyful holiday, or to be happy in life.
.
There is only what YOU NEED to be joyful in your life, and how you advocate for that, releasing everyone else's expectations and your own false expectations.
.
You are exactly enough. You are doing enough.
.
Your kids don't need stuff, they need YOU.
.
Your kids don't need you to be flawless. They need you to be happy.
.
YOU ARE THE MAGIC this season & all seasons. ✨
.

Why Books?

What's the big deal about a book? That is the question I’ve been trying to put into words (I wrote a book & somehow this feels harder). Storytelling is universal & a basic method of human connection. How do I explain why books have such a special place in my heart?

Because books have a unique way of letting you into a character’s head that TV & movies can’t do.

Because sometimes a kid needs a safe place to escape to when their home no longer feels like that place.

Because books provide an immersive experience, drawing a reader in through written word & forcing them to engage by painting a picture in their mind.

Because it gives you an opportunity to travel to worlds you might not otherwise see.

Because sometimes the power goes out.

Because words matter. Word choice matters. Books are a tangible example of how word choice impacts perception & experience.

Because sometimes life feels heavy & you need to lose yourself in something lighter.

Because you can walk in someone else’s shoes & understand another human you’d otherwise never know or understand.

Because you can walk in someone else’s shoes & understand that you aren’t alone.

Because brain health.

Because stories help us make sense of the world we live in.

Because reading books reduces stress (hooray for science).

Because sometimes you need an adventure.

What's the big deal about a book? What makes books so special? Everything.

An open letter to authors,

Gratitude will change everything you experience in your writing journey. They say there's no such thing as bad publicity. Well that is just not true.

At this exact moment in time, a certain author is receiving a lot of backlash after publicly calling a reader, who gave her debut book a 4 star review, a mean name. The reading community has responded by rallying to tank the author's reviews. She's responded to that by gaslighting the community, claiming they can't take a joke.

While I don't really want to give her more attention than she's already received, I do REALLY want to comment on the heart of the matter.

Authors, hear me when I tell you this // there isn't a single book on the planet that is for every person who picks it up. Not one.

That is OK! It doesn't say anything about you as a writer, or you as a human. It speaks only to an individual's experience with your writing.

If you have an average 3 star rating, that's good! An average 4+ stars, that's fantastic!

If someone gives me a 1-2 star rating, I choose gratitude.

Of all the books in the world, that person chose to pick up mine. They invested their time -- time they can never have back -- into reading MY book. That is SO freaking cool! That they didn't connect with it is a bummer. But appreciate the fact that they tried.

If I choose gratitude during the low moments, then I'm a happier human. And I'll continue to enjoy this ride.

Unkindness breeds unkindness. So, I encourage you, writer, to take pride in your work, understand just how hard it is to do what you do, and be grateful to your readers. Each and every single one of them.

You are more than your average rating. Your readers are more than their ratings too.

🫶🏻
Marissa

How-To: Writing & publishing your first book! Tell me what you want to know!! 👇🏼 I'm so excited to share more behind the scenes, processes, tools & tips! Publishing broad strokes, traditional vs indie, writing tips, idea generation, and more! Feel free to pop in with questions along the way!

Welcome to our new series where I'm going to break down the broad strokes of publishing your first book & then we can dive into more of the details of how your book becomes a book. So without further ado...

How to publish to publish your first book // Step One: WRITE THE BOOK!

It sounds like DUH, but truly, it's the biggest reason most people never see their book published. They never finish writing the story to begin with. Or, they never even get started. 

Writing a book is HARD. Make no mistake about it.

But everything about the publishing process can be learned, and you can't publish what you haven't written.

Allow your first draft to be messy, ugly, terribly written. Clean up comes later. This is the part where you are telling yourself the story for the very first time so you can see the bones form.

Today's lesson is a short one, but I'll leave you with one of my favorite quotes about writing: The only thing you can't fix, is a blank page.

We'll get into writing tools, where I write, favorite resources, and tips later on! 

Now put your booty in the chair & go write your story! 

What questions do you have about the writing or publishing process? 👇🏼 Anything at all! I'll cover them all as we make our way through this & future series!

How to Publish Your First Novel / Step 2:  REVISE & EDIT!

You will live here...probably longer than you spent writing your first draft, reading & revising after each layer (multiple times).

Go through the layers as many times as you need to polish your manuscript as much as you possibly can. 

1. Critique / writing partner
2. Developmental edit - this is where you'll handle Structural issues & plot problems 
3. Line edit - this is where you'll worry about prose & Typos 
4. Beta readers
5. Audio Read / Text-to-Speech

One thing I struggled with in this phase is knowing when to call the manuscript DONE. You can honestly stay in this phase forever. You can ALWAYS find things to change. 

If you are having problems with this, chat with your writing partner. Someone who is outside of your work will have a better viewpoint of when your work is ready!

Later on I'll get into specifics of each layer & tools I like to use! For now, any questions? 👇🏼

How to Publish Your First Novel / Step 3:  COPYRIGHT!

So exciting! If you're here, it means you're finished (or very close to) with editing & revision. Time to obtain exclusive rights & protect your ownership of your original work.

Who owns your work? Well, YOU DO. But your copyright helps protect you legally against unlawful acquisition, citation, claims of ownership, and distribution of your work. 

Your manuscript doesn't need to be perfect, but it should be as close to the final product as possible.

You'll apply & submit materials with the US Copyright Office. Your copyright is effective the date your application is submitted though you may not receive notification of approval until days later.

Your copyright is good for the life of the author plus 70 years!

Any questions about this? What else do you wanna know?

How To Publish Your First Novel / Step 4: CHOOSE YOUR PUBLISHING & DISTRIBUTION PARTNERS! 

This is a biggie! It's time for you to start thinking about where you want to sell your book & who you need to partner with to get it there. You can choose as many, or as few as you'd like & who you choose will depend largely on your personal goals. 

Do you want to publish directly on Amazon through KDP? Directly on Barnes & Noble through B&N Press? Do you want to use a single network for wide distribution across all platforms, like Ingram Spark? 

Some food for thought: you'll make a little more money by selling through each individual publishing platform directly... BUT, that's more platform statistics, sales, and data that you need to keep track of.

The majority of your sales will likely come through Amazon BUT... if you dream of being sold in bookstores and Barnes & Noble and the like, you NEED to use a service like Ingram Spark that has a relationship with these partners already. Think about it... Barnes & Noble doesn't want to have to purchase your book from Amazon (their biggest competitor) in order to stock it in their stores. Ingram Spark will give you that wide distribution if you seek that (they distribute to Amazon too -- a much longer discussion).

When it comes to publishing, you CAN use Small Presses, hybrid publishers, and vanity presses to help you get your book ready for publication. BUT, this is going to cost you a pretty penny as an indie author AND they likely won't help you with marketing & distribution either. Something to consider when deciding how much help you need & where you want to outsource.

Again, everything is learnable. You just need to do your research & think about what you want for your writing career & where you want to invest your time & money.

Any questions?

How To Publish Your First Novel / Step 5: FORMAT YOUR WORK! 

AKA interior design! This is the part where you get to decide what your words will look like on the physical & digital page!

You have some options here, depending on budget & how much creative freedom you want to keep.

You can, of course, hire a graphic designer to design & format your book interior. That will cost you a good chunk of money, which most indie authors don't have. Many are working with a shoestring budget on their first novel. This is, however, a nice middle ground on creative freedom since you will be collaborating with your designer to design an interior you love!

6 things you DON’T need to be an author:

1. An MFA // Not anymore. If you have one, great! If you WANT one, awesome. Do you need one to be an author? NOPE! There’s tons of resources to sharpen your skills.

2. To write everyday // I don’t know why… but a lot of writers get it in their head that they have to write daily and hit XYZ word count. No! Life happens. Sometimes the flow isn’t there. Some days, you’ll write a lot, others you won’t write at all. Most of the time you’ll be somewhere in between. It’s all good!

3. To be Traditionally Published // eesh. I feel this one. I did SO much research when deciding on publishing. Indie authors can get a bad wrap (for reasons I won’t get into NOW — a discussion for another day), but the truth is, today, Indie Authors are rocking the scene and taking their rightful place in the book world with tons of support. There’s huge pros and cons to each route. So choose the one best for you and GET IT. 

4. To have perfect command of language // grammer, spelling, punctuation, etc… truth is, no one speaks that way, and no one really writes that way either. You’re telling a story (probably), not being graded in English Lit. 

5. To write “literary fiction” // unless that’s your jam that you WANT to write. You don’t need to be out there competing for the most prosaic novel award. Write what you want to write. No book is for everyone which means there are people that want what you’re writing.

6. To write full time // if that’s your dream, get after it! For sure! But you can also write on the side. It’s hard to carve out a full time gig as a writer. Lots of writers have day jobs. It doesn’t make you NOT a writer.

If I’m being perfectly transparent with you, choosing the title of How It Had To Be was hard. Like, very very hard. Nothing felt right at first. Everything I came up with sounded cheesy or done before (& done better). I was truly at a loss. So, naturally I started researching exactly how titles are chosen. I ended up coming up with a mashup method that worked well for me & I hope it helps you too.   I call it The 10 Post-Its Method. I’m VERY creative (read sarcasm).  It boils down to just a few simple steps:  1. Think of ANY 10 titles that could possibly fit your work. Don’t limit yourself here to what you think is a good title or not. Just let your mind free flow until you have 10 possible titles. Keeping in mind that you can look to trends and popular books on the market to see what is working or to gain some inspiration. Are they one word? Are they a place? Are they dramatic or more factual? Etc...   2. Write 1 title down on a sticky note until you have 10 sticky notes.   3. Hang the notes up in a place that you walk by or see frequently throughout the day. Your closet wall. The bathroom mirror. Your workspace cork board. The refrigerator. The idea being that your subconscious is letting these titles sink in and without even realizing it, you ARE starting to evaluate them. Let your thalamus go to work (that’s the area of the brain responsible for sorting out relevant from irrelevant details and filtering out unnecessary information).   4. Once per day, for 9 days, walk over & remove 1 sticky note that you don’t like, that doesn’t speak to you, or just doesn’t seem to capture the vibe of your work.   5. If you make it to day 9, congrats! You’re now left with one title. Play with that title for a few days. See how it feels rolling off your tongue. Is it growing on you? Does it fit? If not, just repeat the process until you find the ONE.   6. Sometimes, you won’t make it that far. I didn’t. By day 3, one title was jumping out at me and I knew it was IT. I rolled with it and never looked back.   I hope this help you if you’re hung up where I was. This method can be applied to a lot of different aspects in writing and in life.

THREE THINGS I DID TO DESIGN MY OWN COVERS:

No gatekeeping. It’s an incredible feeling to have someone pick up one of my books, compliment the cover, and ask who my cover designer is. My cheeks burn every time I tell them, “me”. I don’t say that to boast. I tell you that because I work really hard to ensure I have a quality cover that looks like it belongs on any major bookstore shelf.   Here’s what I do:

1️⃣ Market research, lots of it. You better believe the big publishing industry is looking way down the road & trends are developed much sooner than a books release date. So look ahead at different covers in your genre around the time your book will release and study the colors, styles, layouts, fonts, etc… to see what’s going to be trending.

2️⃣ Choose a singular focal point that captures the essence of the story without spoiling anything. Too much on the cover can be distracting. A place to draw the readers eye can hook and entice.

3️⃣ I put my covers next to popular books in my genre to see how well it fit in. I just used Canva to lay out images of the covers all together. You want your book to stand out, but you also want it to look like it belongs on a bookshelf next to the heavy hitters.

Don’t worry if design isn’t your jam. Everything is learnable if you invest the time. Short on time? There are tons of fantastic graphic designers that you can outsource to. But don’t be afraid to take on the challenge. You can do it!

🛼 Middle Grade: 20k - 50k words

The bottom line is, ALL books spread by word of mouth... reader reviews, friends recommendations, bookstagrammer shares... what's going to make them share? A great story.

You can invest as much money & time into spreading the word as you want. It might help a ton. It might help a little.

It's not a secret... revision is EXHAUSTING & writers get sick of their own writing QUICK 🤪. But, there are some layers that writers just can't afford to gloss over. Here are the first 6 layers I check my work against:

1. Plot holes & bunny trails: look for loose ends & unanswered questions. One large part of developmental editing.

2. Typos / grammar / punctuation: also known as line editing. This is what most people think of when their hear "editing" though it's just one small (but important) piece.

3. Icebergs: this refers to revealing information on a need to know basis only. Picture the top of the iceberg with so much more lurking beneath the surface. Trust that your reader is smart enough to keep going without all the information right now.

4. Fluff & filler words: google lists of filler words & check for over use. You think you need a lot of these words, especially to bolster your word count. But, listen to how your writing sounds without them. Often it's better. In the same vein, make sure you're not info dumping on your readers (see icebergs above).

5. Showing over telling: paint the picture instead of reading it to your audience. Draw them in. Think sensory info. Visualization. Help your reader FEEL the scene instead of telling them how it should feel. Ask them to engage their imagination.

6. Colorism in all forms: this spans everything from outright prejudice to describing only the "non-white" skin tones & features. Assigning non-white characteristics to lower value. Unflattering & offensive adjectives. Etc...

Let's expand a bit...

1. Having your loved ones read your work is all well and good. BUT... you are far less likely to get constructive feedback. They love you, they want to encourage you & they don't want to hurt your feelings. You NEED these people in your corner! But they likely won't give you the feedback you NEED to improve your story or your writing.

2. In the same vein, you need someone who also writes! Those who don't may not be able to give you the critiques you need to make the story better. They may be well intentioned, but they also might not know HOW to talk about character archs, or rabbit trails, or show vs tell, or filler, or info dumping... a fellow writer or editor is going to be far more helpful when it comes to technical aspects of great writing.

3. An objective overall viewpoint from someone who isn't emotionally tied to the work. You worked SO hard, and you're too close to see what needs to be cut, or expanded on. Elements that don't push the story forward, but that you love, typos & errors your eyes have adapted to glossing over on your 90th revision. You need someone who can step back & look at the big picture without being attached to any one piece and tell you what still needs work.
